# White Pages

We're given a text file called `whitepages.txt`. The file category is forensics so let's start looking into this file.

There aren't any hidden comments and stuff that we can see with `exiftool`, but what we can see (when actually opening the file up) is there are a lot whitespace.

They've probably encoded the flag into whitespace, let's see if the format of it is familiar.

If we copy the the file file as hex string we get the following:

````txt
```

It appears that there are 2 patterns, `28083e`, and `20`. It looks like this is probably binary then.

I replaced `28083e` with `0`, and `20` with `1` to get the following:

```txt

````

If we go to [cryptii](https://cryptii.com) we can decode the message and get:

```txt
picoCTF
SEE PUBLIC RECORDS & BACKGROUND REPORT
5000 Forbes Ave, Pittsburgh, PA 15213
picoCTF{not_all_spaces_are_created_equal_c54f27cd05c2189f8147cc6f5deb2e56}
```

This was pretty easy, and worth 250 points. I think I got lucky with this though, if I had done `1` and `0` instead of `0` and `1` I'd have to flip them, and that would have been annoying.

Now all I wonder is what that adress is...
